<section id="overview">
  <h2>What Is Chinese New Year?</h2>
  <p><strong>Chinese New Year</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>, Ch&#363;nji&#233;) &mdash; also known as the <strong>Spring Festival</strong> &mdash; is the most important traditional festival in Chinese culture. It marks the beginning of a new year on the <a href="/calendar/">Chinese lunisolar calendar</a>, which tracks both the moon's phases and the sun's position along the ecliptic. This makes the Chinese calendar <em>lunisolar</em>, not purely lunar, a distinction that matters: the intercalary month system ensures that the new year always falls between 21 January and 20 February in the Gregorian calendar, anchored to the second new moon after the winter solstice.</p>
  <p>The festival's modern Chinese name, <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> (Spring Festival), was formally adopted in 1914 when the newly established Republic of China designated the first day of the first lunar month as <span class="chinese-char">春節</span> and reserved the term <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> (Yuand&agrave;n) for 1 January on the Gregorian calendar. In classical pre-Ming texts, the lunisolar new year was itself called <span class="chinese-char">元旦</span> &mdash; literally "the first dawn" &mdash; a term attested as early as the Southern Qi dynasty poet Xiao Ziliang's writing and widely used through the Tang and Song periods. Other classical names include <span class="chinese-char">元日</span> (<span class="pinyin">Yu&aacute;nr&igrave;</span>, First Day), <span class="chinese-char">正旦</span> (<span class="pinyin">Zh&egrave;ngd&agrave;n</span>, Correct Dawn), and <span class="chinese-char">歲首</span> (<span class="pinyin">Su&igrave;sh&#466;u</span>, Head of the Year).</p>
  <p>In contemporary China, the Spring Festival triggers <strong>Chunyun</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">春運</span>) &mdash; the Spring Festival travel season &mdash; which is the <strong>largest annual human migration on Earth</strong>. In a typical year, billions of passenger journeys are made over a forty-day window as workers return to their hometowns for the reunion dinner. The festival period officially spans from New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>) through the <strong>Lantern Festival</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>) on the fifteenth day of the first month, though the most intensive celebrations occur during the first seven days.</p>
  <p>In 2026, Chinese New Year falls on <strong>17 February</strong>, ushering in the <a href="/article-2026-horse/">Year of the Fire Horse</a> (<span class="chinese-char">丙午</span>, B&#464;ngw&#468;). The Lantern Festival follows on 3 March 2026.</p>
</section>

<section id="history">
  <h2>Historical Origins</h2>
  <p>The roots of Chinese New Year extend deep into antiquity, predating any single dynasty or written record. The festival evolved over millennia from archaic year-end sacrificial rites into the complex, multi-layered celebration practised today.</p>

  <h3>Shang Dynasty: Oracle Bone Evidence</h3>
  <p>The earliest evidence for year-end rituals comes from <strong>Shang dynasty</strong> (c. 1600&ndash;1046 BCE) oracle bone inscriptions (<span class="chinese-char">甲骨文</span>). These inscriptions, excavated primarily at Yinxu (<span class="chinese-char">殷墟</span>) near modern Anyang, record divinations concerning <span class="chinese-char">祀</span> (sacrificial rites) performed at the transition between one year and the next. While the Shang calendar differed from later systems, the concept of marking the year's turning with sacrifices to ancestors and celestial spirits is unmistakably present. The Shang practiced a cycle of rituals linked to the agricultural year, with the most elaborate ceremonies occurring at year's end to express gratitude for the harvest and petition for blessings in the coming cycle.</p>

  <h3>Zhou Dynasty: Standardising the First Month</h3>
  <p>The <strong>Zhou dynasty</strong> (1046&ndash;256 BCE) systematised the calendar and established the position of the first month (<span class="chinese-char">正月</span>, zh&#275;ngyue). The <em>Shijing</em> (<span class="chinese-char">詩經</span>, Classic of Poetry), compiled during the Western Zhou, contains poems describing year-end celebrations and agricultural rites. The <em>Zhouli</em> (<span class="chinese-char">周禮</span>, Rites of Zhou) documents elaborate state-level ceremonies at the new year, including the <span class="chinese-char">大儺</span> (Great Nuo) exorcism ritual, in which officials and performers drove out pestilence and evil spirits to purify the realm for the year ahead. This Nuo exorcism &mdash; involving masked dancers, drumming, and torchlight processions &mdash; is a direct ancestor of the firecracker and lion-dance traditions that persist today.</p>

  <h3>Han Dynasty: The Taichu Calendar</h3>
  <p>The decisive calendrical reform came under <strong>Emperor Wu of Han</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">漢武帝</span>) in <strong>104 BCE</strong>, when the court astronomer Luoxia Hong (<span class="chinese-char">落下閎</span>) and others devised the <strong>Taichu calendar</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">太初曆</span>). This calendar standardised the first month (<span class="chinese-char">正月</span>) as the beginning of the year, fixing the lunisolar new year to the position it has occupied ever since. Prior to this reform, different dynasties had designated different months as the start of the year &mdash; the Qin dynasty, for instance, had used the tenth month. The Taichu calendar's adoption unified the calendrical system and established the framework within which all subsequent Spring Festival celebrations took shape.</p>
  <p>Han-dynasty sources describe New Year customs that would be recognisable today: door gods (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>) painted or posted to ward off evil, communal drinking and feasting, and the practice of staying up through the night on New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>). The Eastern Han scholar Cui Shi (<span class="chinese-char">崔寔</span>) mentions new-year customs in his <em>Simin Yueling</em> (<span class="chinese-char">四民月令</span>, Monthly Ordinances for the Four Classes of People), providing one of the earliest systematic records of seasonal observances.</p>

  <h3>Liang Dynasty: Jingchu Suishi Ji</h3>
  <p>The most detailed early record of Spring Festival customs is the <strong><em>Jingchu Suishi Ji</em></strong> (<span class="chinese-char">荊楚歲時記</span>, Record of the Seasons of Jingchu), written by <strong>Zong Lin</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">宗懍</span>) of the <a href="/dynasties/">Liang dynasty</a> (502&ndash;557 CE). This remarkable text documents festival practices in the Jingchu region (modern Hubei and Hunan) with extraordinary specificity: setting off bamboo firecrackers (<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>, literally "exploding bamboo" &mdash; bamboo sections thrown into fire to produce loud cracks) at dawn on the first day; drinking <span class="chinese-char">屠蘇酒</span> (tusu wine, a medicinal herbal wine believed to ward off plague); posting <span class="chinese-char">桃符</span> (peachwood charms, precursors to spring couplets); and preparing special foods. Zong Lin's account is the earliest comprehensive source for the customs that define the Spring Festival to this day.</p>

  <h3>Tang, Song, and Beyond</h3>
  <p>During the <strong>Tang dynasty</strong> (618&ndash;907), the Spring Festival became firmly established as both a state holiday and a popular celebration. The Tang poet Wang Anshi (<span class="chinese-char">王安石</span>, <span class="pinyin">W&aacute;ng &#256;nsh&iacute;</span>)'s famous poem <em>Yuanri</em> (<span class="chinese-char">元日</span>) &mdash; "Amid the sound of firecrackers, one year passes; spring breeze brings warmth to tusu wine" &mdash; captures the festive atmosphere, though Wang Anshi was actually a Song-dynasty figure (the poem's enduring popularity across dynasties illustrates the timelessness of these customs). By the <strong>Song dynasty</strong> (960&ndash;1279), commercial printing enabled the mass production of <span class="chinese-char">年畫</span> (New Year prints) and paper-based decorations, transforming the festival's visual culture. The <em>Dongjing Meng Hua Lu</em> (<span class="chinese-char">東京夢華錄</span>, Dreams of Splendour of the Eastern Capital) by Meng Yuanlao (<span class="chinese-char">孟元老</span>, <span class="pinyin">M&egrave;ng Yu&aacute;nl&aacute;o</span>) provides vivid descriptions of Song-dynasty Kaifeng's new-year celebrations: night markets, lantern displays, theatrical performances, and elaborate feasts.</p>
  <p>Through the Ming and Qing dynasties, the festival continued to accumulate traditions &mdash; spring couplets (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>) written with brush calligraphy, red envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>/<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>), dragon and lion dances, and increasingly elaborate reunion dinners. By the modern era, the Spring Festival had become the single most important cultural event in the Chinese world, a festival whose traditions span more than three thousand years of continuous practice.</p>
</section>

<section id="preparations">
  <h2>Pre-New Year Preparations</h2>
  <p>The festival's preparations begin well before New Year's Eve, typically from the twenty-third or twenty-fourth day of the twelfth lunar month. These preparations are not merely practical; each carries symbolic significance rooted in folk religion and cosmological thinking.</p>

  <h3>Little New Year (<span class="chinese-char">小年</span>)</h3>
  <p><strong>Little New Year</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">小年</span>, Xi&#462;oni&aacute;n) falls on the 23rd of the twelfth month in northern China and the 24th in southern China. The central ritual is the <strong>sending off of the Kitchen God</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">灶君</span>/<span class="chinese-char">灶王爺</span>, Z&agrave;oj&#363;n). According to folk belief, the Kitchen God resides in every household and ascends to Heaven on this day to report the family's conduct to the Jade Emperor (<span class="chinese-char">玉皇大帝</span>). Families smear the Kitchen God's paper image with malt sugar (<span class="chinese-char">麥芽糖</span>) or <span class="chinese-char">糖瓜</span> (sugar melons) &mdash; either to sweeten his words or, as the folk saying goes, to glue his lips shut so he cannot speak ill of the household. The image is then burned to send him heavenward, and a new image is posted on New Year's Eve to welcome his return.</p>

  <h3>House Cleaning (<span class="chinese-char">掃塵</span>)</h3>
  <p>A thorough cleaning of the entire house, called <span class="chinese-char">掃塵</span> (s&#462;och&eacute;n, "sweeping the dust"), follows Little New Year. The word <span class="chinese-char">塵</span> (dust) is a homophone of <span class="chinese-char">陳</span> (old, stale), so sweeping the dust symbolises sweeping away the old year's misfortunes, stale energy, and accumulated bad luck. Every corner is cleaned, old items are discarded, and the house is made ready to receive fresh blessings. This practice echoes the ancient Nuo exorcism &mdash; a physical and symbolic purification of the living space.</p>

  <h3>Spring Couplets and Door Gods (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span> &amp; <span class="chinese-char">門神</span>)</h3>
  <p><strong>Spring couplets</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>, ch&#363;nli&aacute;n) are paired lines of poetry written in black or gold ink on red paper, pasted on either side of the doorframe. They express wishes for prosperity, health, and good fortune in the coming year. The tradition descends from the ancient practice of hanging <span class="chinese-char">桃符</span> (peachwood charms) described in the <em>Jingchu Suishi Ji</em>. Ming dynasty emperor Zhu Yuanzhang (<span class="chinese-char">朱元璋</span>) is credited with popularising the practice of writing couplets on red paper, issuing an edict encouraging all households to post spring couplets at the new year.</p>
  <p><strong>Door gods</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>, m&eacute;nsh&eacute;n) &mdash; images of guardian figures posted on the main door &mdash; trace back to the Han dynasty and earlier. The most common door gods are the Tang-dynasty generals Qin Shubao (<span class="chinese-char">秦叔寶</span>) and Yuchi Gong (<span class="chinese-char">尉遲恭</span>), who according to legend stood guard outside Emperor Taizong's chamber to ward off ghosts. Their images, printed on paper, now serve the same protective function symbolically.</p>

  <h3>New Year Shopping (<span class="chinese-char">辦年貨</span>)</h3>
  <p>Families stock up on <span class="chinese-char">年貨</span> (ni&aacute;nhu&ograve;, New Year goods): food ingredients for the reunion dinner and festival period, new clothing (especially in red), candies and dried fruits, firecrackers, decorations, and gifts. Markets and shopping streets bustle with activity in the weeks before the festival, and in modern China, online shopping platforms launch massive Spring Festival sales.</p>

  <h3>Paper-Cutting (<span class="chinese-char">剪紙</span>) and Decorations</h3>
  <p><span class="chinese-char">剪紙</span> (ji&#462;nzh&#464;, paper-cutting) is a traditional folk art used to create intricate red decorations for windows and walls. Common motifs include the character <span class="chinese-char">福</span> (f&uacute;, fortune &mdash; often posted upside-down, since <span class="chinese-char">倒</span>, "inverted," is a homophone of <span class="chinese-char">到</span>, "arrived," symbolising "fortune has arrived"), zodiac animals, flowers, and auspicious symbols. Red lanterns are hung at doorways, and the colour red dominates every surface &mdash; a visual expression of <a href="/wuxing/">Fire-element</a> energy and the ancient belief that red drives away evil spirits.</p>

  <h3>Food Preparation</h3>
  <p>Elaborate food preparation begins days before the reunion dinner. Dumplings (<span class="chinese-char">餃子</span>) are made in enormous quantities, often as a family activity. Rice cakes (<span class="chinese-char">年糕</span>, ni&aacute;ng&aacute;o), whose name is a homophone for "year higher" (<span class="chinese-char">年高</span>), symbolising advancement, are steamed. Dried meats, preserved fish, and candied fruits are prepared or purchased. Each dish carries meaning: nothing is chosen at random.</p>
</section>

<section id="eve">
  <h2>New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>)</h2>
  <p>New Year's Eve (<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>, Ch&uacute;x&#299;) &mdash; literally "Removing the Evening" &mdash; is the emotional and ritual heart of the entire festival. The character <span class="chinese-char">除</span> means to remove or drive out, signifying the expulsion of the old year and its accumulated ills.</p>

  <h3>The Reunion Dinner (<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>)</h3>
  <p>The <strong>reunion dinner</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>, ni&aacute;ny&egrave;f&agrave;n, or <span class="chinese-char">團圓飯</span>, tu&aacute;nyu&aacute;nf&agrave;n) is the single most important meal of the year. Family members travel vast distances to be present; it is this imperative that drives Chunyun. The meal is typically lavish, with dishes chosen for their symbolic meanings:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Dish</th><th>Chinese Name</th><th>Symbolism</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Whole fish</td><td><span class="chinese-char">魚</span> (y&uacute;)</td><td>Surplus and abundance &mdash; <span class="chinese-char">年年有餘</span> (y&uacute; is a homophone of "surplus")</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Dumplings</td><td><span class="chinese-char">餃子</span> (ji&#462;ozi)</td><td>Wealth &mdash; shaped like gold ingots (<span class="chinese-char">元寶</span>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Rice cake</td><td><span class="chinese-char">年糕</span> (ni&aacute;ng&aacute;o)</td><td>Year-on-year advancement &mdash; homophone of <span class="chinese-char">年高</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Spring rolls</td><td><span class="chinese-char">春卷</span> (ch&#363;nju&#462;n)</td><td>Wealth &mdash; resembling gold bars</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tangyuan</td><td><span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span> (t&#257;ngyu&aacute;n)</td><td>Family unity and completeness &mdash; round shape symbolises togetherness</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Chicken</td><td><span class="chinese-char">雞</span> (j&#299;)</td><td>Auspiciousness &mdash; homophone of <span class="chinese-char">吉</span> (j&iacute;, luck)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Longevity noodles</td><td><span class="chinese-char">長壽麵</span> (<span class="pinyin">ch&aacute;ngsh&ograve;umi&agrave;n</span>)</td><td>Long life &mdash; noodles served uncut</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>A place is often set for absent family members. In some regions, a fish is served but deliberately left uneaten to ensure that "surplus" (<span class="chinese-char">餘</span>) carries into the new year.</p>

  <h3>Staying Up: Shousui (<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>)</h3>
  <p><span class="chinese-char">守歲</span> (sh&#466;usu&igrave;, "guarding the year") is the practice of staying awake through the entire night of New Year's Eve. The custom is attested as early as the Jin dynasty, and the <em>Jingchu Suishi Ji</em> records it explicitly for the Liang period. The folk explanation holds that staying up ensures longevity for one's parents; the cosmological dimension is that the vigil marks a conscious transition from the old year's energy to the new, a liminal period during which the family's awareness must remain unbroken. In modern practice, families watch the CCTV Spring Festival Gala (<span class="chinese-char">春節聯歡晚會</span>), play games, and eat snacks through the night.</p>

  <h3>Firecrackers at Midnight</h3>
  <p>At midnight, an eruption of <strong>firecrackers</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>/<span class="chinese-char">鞭炮</span>) marks the new year's arrival. This practice descends directly from the Liang-dynasty custom recorded by Zong Lin: throwing bamboo into fire to produce explosive cracks that frighten away evil spirits. The invention of gunpowder during the Tang dynasty transformed bamboo crackers into paper-wrapped firecrackers, and the practice grew in scale and intensity through subsequent dynasties. The folk legend of <strong>Nian</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>), a fearsome beast that emerged at year's end to terrorise villages, provides the popular explanation: Nian was discovered to fear loud noises, bright light, and the colour red, which is why firecrackers, lanterns, and red decorations became the festival's defining features.</p>

  <h3>Red Envelopes (<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>)</h3>
  <p><strong>Red envelopes</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>, h&oacute;ngb&#257;o, or <span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>, y&#257;su&igrave;qi&aacute;n, "money to suppress the year-spirit") containing money are given by elders to children and unmarried younger relatives. The practice dates to at least the Song dynasty. The <span class="chinese-char">壓</span> in <span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span> means "to suppress" &mdash; the money is believed to protect children from evil spirits (<span class="chinese-char">祟</span>, su&igrave;, a homophone of <span class="chinese-char">歲</span>, su&igrave;) during the vulnerable transition between years. Red envelopes are typically given after the reunion dinner or on New Year's Day. In modern practice, digital red envelopes via WeChat and Alipay have become enormously popular, with billions distributed electronically each festival season.</p>

  <h3>New Clothes</h3>
  <p>Wearing new clothing &mdash; especially in <strong>red</strong> &mdash; on New Year's Day symbolises a fresh start and the shedding of the old year's energy. Red, as the colour of the <a href="/wuxing/">Fire element</a>, represents vitality, prosperity, and protection. Children in particular are dressed entirely in red from head to toe.</p>
</section>

<section id="traditions">
  <h2>Day-by-Day Traditions</h2>
  <p>The fifteen days from New Year's Day to the Lantern Festival each carry specific customs, though observance varies by region. The following outlines the most widely practised traditions.</p>

  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Day</th><th>Name</th><th>Key Traditions</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 1</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初一</span>)</td>
        <td>New Year's Day</td>
        <td>Visit elder relatives to pay respects (<span class="chinese-char">拜年</span>). Set off firecrackers at dawn. Wear new clothes. Eat dumplings (north) or rice cakes (south). Avoid sweeping (to prevent sweeping away good fortune), using sharp objects, and speaking inauspicious words.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 2</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初二</span>)</td>
        <td>Married daughters return (<span class="chinese-char">回娘家</span>)</td>
        <td>Married women return to visit their birth families, accompanied by their husbands and children. This is a major social occasion. Gifts are brought for the natal family. In some traditions, the God of Wealth (<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>) is welcomed on this day.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 3</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初三</span>)</td>
        <td>Day of Rest / Red Mouth (<span class="chinese-char">赤口</span>)</td>
        <td>Traditionally considered an inauspicious day for visiting, as it is believed to invite quarrels (<span class="chinese-char">赤口</span>, "red mouth," denotes arguments). Families rest at home. In some regions, this is the day that the mouse marries (<span class="chinese-char">老鼠嫁女</span>), and families retire early to give the mice their celebration.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 4</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初四</span>)</td>
        <td>Welcome the Kitchen God</td>
        <td>The Kitchen God (<span class="chinese-char">灶君</span>) returns from his heavenly report. Families prepare offerings and a new image. In folk belief, the gods descend from Heaven to inspect the mortal realm on this day.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 5</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初五</span>)</td>
        <td>Break Five / Welcome the God of Wealth (<span class="chinese-char">破五</span>/<span class="chinese-char">迎財神</span>)</td>
        <td>A pivotal day. The taboos of the first four days are lifted (<span class="chinese-char">破五</span>, "breaking the five"). Firecrackers are set off energetically to welcome the <strong>God of Wealth</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>, C&aacute;ish&eacute;n). Businesses traditionally reopen. Dumplings are eaten to symbolise wealth. This is one of the noisiest days of the festival.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 6</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初六</span>)</td>
        <td>Send Off the God of Poverty</td>
        <td>Rubbish accumulated during the first five days (when sweeping was forbidden) is finally taken out, symbolically sending away the God of Poverty (<span class="chinese-char">送窮</span>). Shops and markets fully resume operations.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 7</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">初七</span>)</td>
        <td>Renri &mdash; Birthday of Humanity (<span class="chinese-char">人日</span>)</td>
        <td><strong>Renri</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">人日</span>, R&eacute;nr&igrave;) is the "Birthday of Humanity," based on the creation myth recorded in the <em>Jingchu Suishi Ji</em> which holds that N&uuml;wa (<span class="chinese-char">女媧</span>) created different beings on each of the first seven days: chicken on Day 1, dog on Day 2, pig on Day 3, sheep on Day 4, ox on Day 5, horse on Day 6, and humans on Day 7. Special foods include <span class="chinese-char">七寶羹</span> (seven-treasure congee) made with seven types of vegetables. In southern China and among overseas Chinese communities, Renri remains widely celebrated.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Days 8&ndash;14</strong></td>
        <td>Festival continuation</td>
        <td>Day 8 is associated with grain and the Jade Emperor's birth eve. Day 9 marks the <strong>Jade Emperor's birthday</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">天公生</span>, <span class="pinyin">Ti&#257;ng&#333;ng Sh&#275;ng</span>), observed especially among Hokkien communities with lavish offerings. Days 10&ndash;14 involve continued visiting, temple worship, and preparation for the Lantern Festival.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Day 15</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">正月十五</span>)</td>
        <td>Lantern Festival (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>)</td>
        <td>The <strong>Lantern Festival</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>, Yu&aacute;nxi&#257;oji&eacute;) closes the Spring Festival period. Families eat <span class="chinese-char">元宵</span>/<span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span> (glutinous rice balls, symbolising reunion). Elaborate <strong>lantern displays</strong> fill public spaces, and <span class="chinese-char">猜燈謎</span> (guessing lantern riddles) is a beloved intellectual game. In some regions, lion dances, dragon dances, and stilt-walking performances mark the evening. The Lantern Festival is also associated with romance &mdash; in ancient times, it was one of the few occasions when young women could be seen in public, and the full moon and lantern light made it a setting for romantic encounters.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section id="zodiac-connection">
  <h2>The Zodiac and the New Year</h2>
  <p>The Chinese New Year is the moment when the <a href="/zodiac/">zodiac animal</a> changes in popular understanding. When people say "2026 is the Year of the Horse," they mean that the Horse governs the period beginning on Chinese New Year's Day (17 February 2026) and ending on the eve of the following Chinese New Year (5 February 2027). This is the convention used in everyday Chinese culture, horoscopes, and the assignment of zodiac signs to birth years.</p>
  <p>However, in <a href="/bazi/">BaZi</a> (Four Pillars of Destiny) &mdash; the formal system of Chinese astrological analysis &mdash; the year pillar changes not at Chinese New Year but at <strong>Lichun</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">立春</span>, <span class="pinyin">L&igrave;ch&#363;n</span>, Start of Spring), which falls on 3, 4, or 5 February in the Gregorian calendar (4 February in most years). This means that a person born between Chinese New Year and Lichun occupies a borderline position: popular culture assigns them to the new year's animal, while BaZi practitioners may assign them to the previous year's animal. This distinction matters for anyone seeking a professional <a href="/bazi/">BaZi chart reading</a>.</p>

  <h3>Ben Ming Nian (<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>): Your Zodiac Year</h3>
  <p>Every twelve years, each person encounters their <strong>Ben Ming Nian</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>) &mdash; the year governed by their own birth animal. In 2026, this applies to those born in the Year of the Horse (1942, 1954, 1966, 1978, 1990, 2002, 2014). Tradition holds that one's zodiac year is a time of instability, not because the animal is malevolent but because the year's Earthly Branch clashes with itself (<span class="chinese-char">犯太歲</span>, <span class="pinyin">f&agrave;n T&agrave;isu&igrave;</span>, "offending the Grand Duke Jupiter").</p>
  <p>To counteract the potential challenges of Ben Ming Nian, tradition prescribes:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Wearing red</strong> &mdash; Particularly <strong>red underwear</strong> (<span class="chinese-char">紅內衣</span>) and a red string or belt, ideally given by an elder. Red's association with the <a href="/wuxing/">Fire element</a> provides protective energy.</li>
    <li><strong>Visiting a temple</strong> at the start of the year to pray for protection and peace.</li>
    <li><strong>Exercising caution</strong> with major life decisions: marriage, job changes, large investments, and long-distance moves are traditionally approached with extra deliberation during one's zodiac year.</li>
    <li><strong>Wearing jade or gold</strong> amulets for additional protective energy.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>It is important to note that Ben Ming Nian is a folk tradition rooted in popular astrology. In formal BaZi analysis, the interaction between the year pillar and one's birth chart is far more nuanced than a blanket prescription of caution. A skilled practitioner examines how the returning branch interacts with all four pillars and the current luck cycle before making any assessment. See the <a href="/lucky-colors-numbers-2026/">2026 lucky colours and numbers guide</a> for zodiac-specific recommendations.</p>
</section>

<section id="global">
  <h2>Global Celebrations</h2>
  <p>Chinese New Year is celebrated far beyond the borders of China, making it one of the world's most widely observed cultural festivals. Its global reach reflects centuries of Chinese migration and the enduring cultural cohesion of the Chinese diaspora.</p>

  <h3>Public Holidays</h3>
  <p>The Spring Festival is an official public holiday in: <strong>China</strong> (seven days), <strong>Hong Kong</strong> (three days), <strong>Macau</strong> (three days), <strong>Taiwan</strong> (at least five days), <strong>Singapore</strong> (two days), <strong>Malaysia</strong> (two days), <strong>Indonesia</strong> (one day, Imlek), <strong>Philippines</strong> (one day, since 2012), <strong>South Korea</strong> (three days, as Seollal), and <strong>Vietnam</strong> (typically seven days, as T&#7871;t Nguy&ecirc;n &#272;&aacute;n). Each country's celebration incorporates local customs alongside the core Chinese traditions, creating a rich tapestry of regional variation.</p>

  <h3>Chinatown Celebrations Worldwide</h3>
  <p>Major Chinatown districts in <strong>London</strong>, <strong>San Francisco</strong>, <strong>New York</strong>, <strong>Sydney</strong>, <strong>Vancouver</strong>, <strong>Paris</strong>, and dozens of other cities host spectacular New Year celebrations featuring lion and dragon dances, fireworks, food festivals, and cultural performances. The San Francisco Chinese New Year Parade, established in the 1860s during the Gold Rush era, is one of the oldest and largest outside Asia. London's celebrations in Trafalgar Square and the West End attract hundreds of thousands of visitors. These events serve not only as cultural celebrations for the Chinese community but as bridges of cultural exchange that introduce Chinese traditions to global audiences.</p>

  <h3>Diaspora Traditions</h3>
  <p>For overseas Chinese communities, the Spring Festival serves as the primary anchor of cultural identity. Families maintain reunion dinner traditions, red envelope giving, temple visits, and ancestral worship regardless of where they live. Chinese community organisations, schools, and cultural centres organise festivals, performances, and workshops that preserve traditions and transmit them to younger generations born abroad. The festival's capacity to sustain cultural continuity across generations and continents is one of its most remarkable qualities.</p>

  <h3>Vietnamese T&#7871;t and Korean Seollal</h3>
  <p>While this article focuses on the Chinese celebration, it is worth noting that the lunisolar new year is observed independently in <strong>Vietnam</strong> (as T&#7871;t) and <strong>South Korea</strong> (as Seollal). These celebrations share the same calendrical basis but have developed distinct national traditions: T&#7871;t features b&aacute;nh ch&#432;ng (sticky rice cakes) and ancestral altar offerings, while Seollal centres on tteokguk (rice cake soup) and deep bows (sebae) to elders. The Tibetan new year, <strong>Losar</strong>, follows a slightly different calendar but shares conceptual roots. The umbrella term "Lunar New Year" acknowledges this broader cultural family while respecting each tradition's distinctiveness.</p>
</section>

</div>

<div class="lang-tc">

<section id="overview">
  <h2>甚麼是農曆新年？</h2>
  <p><strong>農曆新年</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>）是中華文化中最重要的傳統節日，標誌着<a href="/calendar/">中國陰陽合曆</a>新一年的開始。中國曆法同時追蹤月相與太陽在黃道上的位置，因此屬於<strong>陰陽合曆</strong>而非純陰曆——這一區別至關重要：置閏月的機制確保了農曆新年始終落在公曆1月21日至2月20日之間，即冬至後第二個朔日。</p>
  <p>「春節」之名正式確立於<strong>1914年</strong>，民國政府將農曆正月初一定名為<span class="chinese-char">春節</span>，而將公曆1月1日保留為<span class="chinese-char">元旦</span>。在明代以前的古籍中，陰陽合曆新年本身即被稱為<span class="chinese-char">元旦</span>——字面意思為「第一個黎明」——此稱謂至遲見於南齊蕭子良的文獻，唐宋兩代廣泛使用。其他古稱包括<span class="chinese-char">元日</span>、<span class="chinese-char">正旦</span>和<span class="chinese-char">歲首</span>。</p>
  <p>在當代中國，春節引發<strong>春運</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">春運</span>）——<strong>全球規模最大的年度人口遷徙</strong>。在約四十天的窗口期內，數十億人次的旅客踏上歸鄉之路，只為趕赴除夕的團圓飯。節慶期間自除夕（<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>）延續至正月十五的<strong>元宵節</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>），但最密集的慶祝活動集中在頭七天。</p>
  <p>2026年農曆新年為<strong>2月17日</strong>，開啟<a href="/article-2026-horse/">丙午火馬年</a>（<span class="chinese-char">丙午</span>）。元宵節為2026年3月3日。</p>
</section>

<section id="history">
  <h2>歷史淵源</h2>
  <p>農曆新年的根源深植於上古時代，早於任何單一王朝或文字記載。這一節日經數千年演變，從遠古歲末祭祀儀式發展為今日豐富多層的慶典。</p>

  <h3>商代：甲骨文的證據</h3>
  <p>歲末祭祀的最早證據來自<strong>商代</strong>（約前1600—前1046年）的甲骨文（<span class="chinese-char">甲骨文</span>）。這些出土於安陽殷墟（<span class="chinese-char">殷墟</span>）的刻辭記載了新舊年交替之際進行的<span class="chinese-char">祀</span>（祭祀儀式）卜問。商代曆法雖與後世不同，但以祭祀祖先和天神來標記歲序更替的概念已清晰可辨。商人圍繞農業周期舉行系列祭儀，歲末的儀式最為隆重，以感謝豐收並祈求來年福佑。</p>

  <h3>周代：確立正月</h3>
  <p><strong>周代</strong>（前1046—前256年）系統化了曆法，確定了正月（<span class="chinese-char">正月</span>）的位置。《詩經》（<span class="chinese-char">詩經</span>）中有描述歲末慶典和農事祭禮的篇章。《周禮》（<span class="chinese-char">周禮</span>）記載了新年時舉行的國家級盛大典禮，包括<span class="chinese-char">大儺</span>（大儺驅邪儀式）：官員與表演者以面具、鼓樂和火把遊行驅逐瘟疫邪祟，淨化國土迎接新年。這一儺祭——涉及面具舞者、擊鼓和火炬巡遊——是今日爆竹與舞獅傳統的直接先驅。</p>

  <h3>漢代：太初曆</h3>
  <p>決定性的曆法改革發生在<strong>漢武帝</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">漢武帝</span>）時期的<strong>公元前104年</strong>，天文學家落下閎（<span class="chinese-char">落下閎</span>）等人編制了<strong>太初曆</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">太初曆</span>）。太初曆將正月（<span class="chinese-char">正月</span>）標準化為歲首，確立了陰陽合曆新年至今不變的位置。此前各代以不同月份為年始——秦代以十月為歲首。太初曆的採用統一了曆法體系，奠定了此後所有春節慶典的時間框架。</p>
  <p>漢代文獻已描述了今人一望即知的新年習俗：張貼門神（<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>）以驅邪、聚飲歡宴、以及除夕守歲（<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>）。東漢學者崔寔（<span class="chinese-char">崔寔</span>）在《四民月令》（<span class="chinese-char">四民月令</span>）中記述了新年風俗，是最早的系統性時令民俗記錄之一。</p>

  <h3>南朝梁：《荊楚歲時記》</h3>
  <p>關於春節習俗最為詳盡的早期記載是<strong>《荊楚歲時記》</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">荊楚歲時記</span>），由<a href="/dynasties/">南朝梁</a>（502—557年）<strong>宗懍</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">宗懍</span>）所撰。此書以極高的具體性記錄了荊楚地區（今湖北、湖南）的節日習俗：正月初一黎明燃放爆竹（<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>，即將竹節投入火中使之爆裂發聲）；飲屠蘇酒（<span class="chinese-char">屠蘇酒</span>，一種辟瘟草藥酒）；掛桃符（<span class="chinese-char">桃符</span>，春聯的前身）；以及備製特色食品。宗懍的記載是迄今所知關於春節習俗的最早綜合文獻。</p>

  <h3>唐宋及其後</h3>
  <p><strong>唐代</strong>（618—907年）春節已牢固確立為國家假日與民間盛事。宋代王安石的名詩《元日》——「爆竹聲中一歲除，春風送暖入屠蘇」——至今傳誦。至<strong>宋代</strong>（960—1279年），雕版印刷的普及催生了年畫（<span class="chinese-char">年畫</span>）與紙質裝飾的大規模生產，深刻改變了節日的視覺文化。孟元老的《東京夢華錄》（<span class="chinese-char">東京夢華錄</span>）生動描繪了宋代開封的新年盛況：夜市、花燈、戲曲表演和豐盛筵席。</p>
  <p>歷經明清兩代，春節持續積累新傳統——毛筆書寫的春聯（<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>）、紅包（<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>/<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>）、舞龍舞獅、日益豐盛的年夜飯。至現代，春節已成為華人世界最重要的文化盛事，其傳統綿延逾三千年。</p>
</section>

<section id="preparations">
  <h2>年前準備</h2>
  <p>節日的準備工作通常始於臘月二十三或二十四日，遠在除夕之前。每一項準備都不僅是實務性的，更承載着源自民間信仰和宇宙觀的象徵意義。</p>

  <h3>小年（<span class="chinese-char">小年</span>）</h3>
  <p><strong>小年</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">小年</span>）在北方為臘月二十三、南方為二十四。核心儀式是<strong>送灶</strong>——送灶君（<span class="chinese-char">灶君</span>/<span class="chinese-char">灶王爺</span>）上天。民間信仰認為灶君常駐每家每戶，此日升天向玉皇大帝（<span class="chinese-char">玉皇大帝</span>）稟報一家善惡。家人以麥芽糖（<span class="chinese-char">麥芽糖</span>）或糖瓜（<span class="chinese-char">糖瓜</span>）塗抹灶君像之嘴——或為甜其言辭，或如俗語所云——粘住嘴巴使之不能說壞話。隨後焚化舊像送其上天，除夕再貼新像迎其歸來。</p>

  <h3>掃塵（<span class="chinese-char">掃塵</span>）</h3>
  <p>小年過後，家家戶戶進行徹底的大掃除，稱為<span class="chinese-char">掃塵</span>。「塵」與「陳」（舊、陳腐）諧音，掃塵象徵掃除舊年的晦氣、陳舊能量和積累的霉運。屋裏的每個角落都要打掃乾淨，舊物丟棄，為迎接新年福氣做好準備。此習俗與古代大儺驅邪一脈相承——是對生活空間的物質性和象徵性淨化。</p>

  <h3>春聯與門神</h3>
  <p><strong>春聯</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">春聯</span>）是以黑或金墨書寫於紅紙上的對仗詩句，貼於門框兩側，表達對新年富貴、健康、吉祥的祝願。此傳統源自《荊楚歲時記》所載的懸掛桃符（<span class="chinese-char">桃符</span>）之俗。明太祖朱元璋（<span class="chinese-char">朱元璋</span>）曾下令鼓勵家家戶戶貼春聯，推動了在紅紙上書寫對聯這一做法的普及。</p>
  <p><strong>門神</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">門神</span>）——貼於大門上的守護神像——可追溯至漢代乃至更早。最常見的門神是唐代將領秦叔寶（<span class="chinese-char">秦叔寶</span>）和尉遲恭（<span class="chinese-char">尉遲恭</span>），傳說二人曾守衛唐太宗寢殿以驅鬼鎮邪。</p>

  <h3>辦年貨與裝飾</h3>
  <p>家家戶戶採購<span class="chinese-char">年貨</span>：年夜飯食材、新衣（尤以紅色為主）、糖果乾果、鞭炮、裝飾品和禮物。剪紙（<span class="chinese-char">剪紙</span>）是傳統民間藝術，用以剪制窗花和牆飾，常見圖案包括「福」字（常倒貼——因「倒」與「到」諧音，寓意「福到了」）、生肖動物和吉祥圖案。紅燈籠高掛門前，紅色佔據每一處視覺空間——這是<a href="/wuxing/">火元素</a>能量的具象表達，也承載着紅色驅邪的古老信仰。</p>

  <h3>食物準備</h3>
  <p>年夜飯的食材準備工作在除夕前數日即已展開。餃子（<span class="chinese-char">餃子</span>）大量包製，常為全家協作；年糕（<span class="chinese-char">年糕</span>，與「年高」諧音，寓步步高升）蒸好備用；臘肉、鹹魚、蜜餞逐一備齊。每道菜都有其寓意，絕非隨意選取。</p>
</section>

<section id="eve">
  <h2>除夕（<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>）</h2>
  <p>除夕（<span class="chinese-char">除夕</span>）是整個春節的情感與禮俗核心。「除」字意為驅除、去除，象徵送走舊年及其積累的不祥。</p>

  <h3>年夜飯（<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>）</h3>
  <p><strong>年夜飯</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">年夜飯</span>，又稱<span class="chinese-char">團圓飯</span>）是全年最重要的一餐。家人不遠千里趕回團聚，正是這一召喚驅動了春運。飯菜極為豐盛，每道菜均因其象徵意義而入選：</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>菜餚</th><th>名稱</th><th>寓意</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>全魚</td><td><span class="chinese-char">魚</span></td><td>年年有餘——「魚」與「餘」諧音</td></tr>
      <tr><td>餃子</td><td><span class="chinese-char">餃子</span></td><td>招財進寶——形似元寶（<span class="chinese-char">元寶</span>）</td></tr>
      <tr><td>年糕</td><td><span class="chinese-char">年糕</span></td><td>步步高升——「糕」與「高」諧音</td></tr>
      <tr><td>春卷</td><td><span class="chinese-char">春卷</span></td><td>黃金萬兩——形似金條</td></tr>
      <tr><td>湯圓</td><td><span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span></td><td>團圓美滿——圓形象徵團聚</td></tr>
      <tr><td>雞</td><td><span class="chinese-char">雞</span></td><td>大吉大利——「雞」與「吉」諧音</td></tr>
      <tr><td>長壽麵</td><td><span class="chinese-char">長壽麵</span></td><td>健康長壽——麵條不剪斷</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>守歲（<span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>）</h3>
  <p><span class="chinese-char">守歲</span>是除夕通宵不眠的習俗，至遲見於晉代文獻，《荊楚歲時記》亦有明確記載。民間認為守歲可為父母增壽；其宇宙觀內涵在於，守夜者以清醒的意識跨越新舊年之交的過渡時刻。現代家庭多以觀看央視春節聯歡晚會（<span class="chinese-char">春節聯歡晚會</span>）、玩遊戲、吃零食的方式守歲。</p>

  <h3>爆竹與紅包</h3>
  <p>午夜時分，<strong>爆竹</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">爆竹</span>/<span class="chinese-char">鞭炮</span>）齊鳴，宣告新年到來。此俗直接承襲宗懍所記「正旦燃爆竹」之例。民間傳說以<strong>年獸</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">年獸</span>）——一頭歲末出沒的凶獸——作為解釋：人們發現年獸畏懼巨響、強光和紅色，遂有了鞭炮、花燈和紅色裝飾的傳統。</p>
  <p><strong>紅包</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">紅包</span>，又稱<span class="chinese-char">壓歲錢</span>）由長輩贈予晚輩和未婚後輩。「壓歲」之「壓」為鎮壓之意——錢幣被認為能鎮壓「祟」（<span class="chinese-char">祟</span>，與「歲」諧音），保護孩童在新舊年交替的易感時刻免受邪祟侵擾。此俗至少可追溯至宋代。在現代，微信和支付寶的電子紅包已極為盛行，每年春節期間有數十億份電子紅包發出。</p>

  <h3>穿新衣</h3>
  <p>新年穿新衣——尤其是<strong>紅色</strong>新衣——象徵新的開始和舊年能量的脫去。紅色作為<a href="/wuxing/">火元素</a>之色，代表生命力、繁榮和護佑。兒童尤其要從頭到腳穿戴一新的紅色衣物。</p>
</section>

<section id="traditions">
  <h2>逐日習俗</h2>
  <p>從初一到十五的十五天中，每天都有特定的習俗，但各地遵行程度不一。以下概述最為普遍的傳統。</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>日期</th><th>名稱</th><th>主要習俗</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>初一</strong></td>
        <td>新年</td>
        <td>向長輩拜年（<span class="chinese-char">拜年</span>）。清晨放鞭炮。穿新衣。吃餃子（北方）或年糕（南方）。忌掃地（免掃走財氣）、忌用利器、忌說不吉利的話。</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>初二</strong></td>
        <td>回娘家（<span class="chinese-char">回娘家</span>）</td>
        <td>出嫁的女兒攜丈夫、兒女回娘家探望。此為重要的社交場合，須帶禮物。部分地區在此日迎接財神（<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>）。</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>初三</strong></td>
        <td>赤口（<span class="chinese-char">赤口</span>）</td>
        <td>傳統認為初三不宜走親訪友，因恐招致口角（<span class="chinese-char">赤口</span>意指爭吵）。全家留在家中休息。部分地區視此日為「老鼠嫁女」（<span class="chinese-char">老鼠嫁女</span>）之夜，早早就寢以讓鼠輩舉行婚禮。</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>初五</strong></td>
        <td>破五/<span class="chinese-char">迎財神</span></td>
        <td>關鍵一天。初一至初四的禁忌於此日解除（<span class="chinese-char">破五</span>）。大放鞭炮迎接<strong>財神</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">財神</span>）。商鋪傳統上在此日開門營業。食餃子以象徵招財。此日為節慶期間最熱鬧的日子之一。</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>初七</strong></td>
        <td>人日（<span class="chinese-char">人日</span>）</td>
        <td><strong>人日</strong>為「人類的生日」，依據《荊楚歲時記》所載創世神話：女媧（<span class="chinese-char">女媧</span>）於頭七日依次造雞、狗、豬、羊、牛、馬、人。特色食品有七寶羹（<span class="chinese-char">七寶羹</span>），以七種蔬菜煮成。在華南地區和海外華人社群中，人日仍廣泛慶祝。</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>十五</strong></td>
        <td>元宵節（<span class="chinese-char">元宵節</span>）</td>
        <td><strong>元宵節</strong>為春節慶典的終章。家人食元宵/<span class="chinese-char">湯圓</span>（寓意團圓）。精美花燈遍佈公共場所，猜燈謎（<span class="chinese-char">猜燈謎</span>）是備受喜愛的智力遊戲。部分地區有舞獅、舞龍、踩高蹺等表演。元宵節亦與浪漫情愫相聯——古時此夜為少數女子可公開露面的場合，明月花燈之下，不乏邂逅佳話。</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section id="zodiac-connection">
  <h2>生肖與新年</h2>
  <p>農曆新年是民間認定<a href="/zodiac/">生肖</a>更替的時刻。當人們說「2026年是馬年」時，指的是自農曆新年（2026年2月17日）起至下一個農曆除夕（2027年2月5日）止的時段。這是日常文化、運勢預測和生肖歸屬中通用的標準。</p>
  <p>然而在<a href="/bazi/">八字</a>命理學中，年柱的更替並非在農曆新年，而是在<strong>立春</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">立春</span>），通常為公曆2月3、4或5日。這意味着在農曆新年與立春之間出生的人處於交界地帶：民俗將其歸入新年生肖，而八字師可能將其歸入前一年的生肖。對於需要專業<a href="/bazi/">八字排盤</a>的人而言，此區別十分重要。</p>

  <h3>本命年（<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>）</h3>
  <p>每十二年，每個人都會遇到自己的<strong>本命年</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">本命年</span>）——與出生生肖相同的年份。2026年適用於馬年出生者（1942、1954、1966、1978、1990、2002、2014年）。傳統認為本命年是不穩定之年，原因在於該年地支與自身相同，即所謂<span class="chinese-char">犯太歲</span>。</p>
  <p>化解本命年挑戰的傳統做法包括：</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>穿紅色</strong>——尤其是<strong>紅色內衣</strong>（<span class="chinese-char">紅內衣</span>）和紅繩或紅腰帶，最好由長輩贈送。紅色承載<a href="/wuxing/">火元素</a>的護佑能量。</li>
    <li><strong>年初赴寺廟祈福</strong>，祈求平安順遂。</li>
    <li><strong>審慎對待重大決策</strong>：婚嫁、轉職、大額投資、長途遷移等在本命年宜格外深思熟慮。</li>
    <li>佩戴<strong>玉器或金飾護身符</strong>以增強護佑能量。</li>
  </ul>
  <p>須指出，本命年屬民間俗信。在正式的八字分析中，年柱與命盤的互動遠比一概而論的「宜謹慎」複雜得多。詳見<a href="/lucky-colors-numbers-2026/">2026年幸運顏色與數字指南</a>中各生肖的專屬建議。</p>
</section>

<section id="global">
  <h2>全球慶祝</h2>
  <p>農曆新年的慶祝遠超中國國境，使其成為世界上最廣泛遵循的文化節日之一。其全球影響力反映了數百年來華人遷徙史及海外華人社群持久的文化凝聚力。</p>

  <h3>公眾假期</h3>
  <p>春節是以下國家和地區的法定公眾假期：<strong>中國</strong>（七天）、<strong>香港</strong>（三天）、<strong>澳門</strong>（三天）、<strong>台灣</strong>（至少五天）、<strong>新加坡</strong>（兩天）、<strong>馬來西亞</strong>（兩天）、<strong>印尼</strong>（一天，稱Imlek）、<strong>菲律賓</strong>（一天，自2012年起）、<strong>韓國</strong>（三天，稱Seollal/설날）和<strong>越南</strong>（通常七天，稱T&#7871;t Nguy&ecirc;n &#272;&aacute;n）。各國慶祝方式融合了當地習俗與核心華人傳統，構成豐富的地域差異。</p>

  <h3>全球唐人街慶典</h3>
  <p><strong>倫敦</strong>、<strong>三藩市</strong>、<strong>紐約</strong>、<strong>悉尼</strong>、<strong>溫哥華</strong>、<strong>巴黎</strong>等城市的唐人街均舉辦盛大的新年慶典，包括舞獅舞龍、煙花、美食節和文化表演。三藩市的農曆新年遊行始於1860年代淘金熱時期，是亞洲以外歷史最悠久、規模最大的慶典之一。這些活動既是華人社群的文化慶典，也是向全球觀眾展示中華傳統的文化交流橋樑。</p>

  <h3>越南春節與韓國春節</h3>
  <p>陰陽合曆新年在<strong>越南</strong>（T&#7871;t）和<strong>韓國</strong>（설날/Seollal）作為獨立的國家節日慶祝。越南的T&#7871;t以粽子（b&aacute;nh ch&#432;ng）和祖先祭壇為特色，韓國的설날則以年糕湯（떡국/tteokguk）和跪拜長輩（歲拜/세배）為核心。藏曆新年（<strong>Losar</strong>）遵循略有不同的曆法但共享概念根源。「農曆新年」（Lunar New Year）作為包容性的統稱，在尊重各傳統獨特性的同時承認了這一更廣泛的文化家族。</p>
</section>

